  Quick definitions

  EV = Expected Value — the average payoff weighted by probability of success. "High-EV" = worth doing because (chance it works) × (size of the win) is large. When I say
  "config tuning is low-EV, deeper search is high-EV," I mean: tuning might work but the gain is small; search is a bigger swing.

  <important>Low-noise gauntlet — a gauntlet is a fixed panel of opponent bots we benchmark against. "Low-noise" means we play enough seat-rotated games (n≈150–200) that the measured
  win-rate has a tight confidence interval (±~5%) instead of a wide one (±18% at n=28). Why it's the linchpin: an autoresearch ratchet keeps a change if the metric
  improves — but if the metric is noisy, random noise looks like improvement and you ratchet on garbage. That's literally what bit us in the forks experiment (a "61% win"
  that was noise and evaporated). The gauntlet manufactures a trustworthy metric out of stochastic games. Your caveat paragraph is exactly correct — Karpathy's
  autoresearch had a deterministic metric (val_bpb), ours is stochastic, so the evaluator is the whole ballgame.</important>

  Karpathy's autoresearch — what I make of it

  I read the actual repo. It's an elegant pattern, not a reusable tool: a three-file contract (prepare.py = fixed evaluator, train.py = agent-editable code, program.md =
  human directions) + a 5-minute "ratchet" that keeps only changes improving val_bpb. The repo itself says it's "purpose-built for tiny LLM training… not a general
  framework." So we don't use it — we reimplement its pattern with our gauntlet as prepare.py, the bot as train.py, and "raise win% / don't bust the time budget" as
  program.md, with Claude Code as the agent. The shape is perfect; the only hard part is the low-noise evaluator (above), which is why I built it first.

  The data that settles your open questions

  <important>- Is comet_reaper 1-ply or does it search? 1-ply greedy. It builds an 18-turn forward projection (assuming everyone does nothing) and greedily fires the best-scoring
  wave — but it does no search over its own or opponents' future decisions. So the 30× headroom is genuinely unspent. ✅ confirms deeper search is the lever.
  - comet_reaper's no-op rate: launches on only 22% of turns (78% "no-op"), but dispatches ~5,700 ships/game. So it's selective, not pathologically passive — it holds
  unless there's a +ROI wave, then commits hard. That's different from the RL no-op trap (which never attacks). It beats the whole field with 22%.
  - The Optuna study, early read (14 trials): best config so far wins only 20% vs comet_reaper — and the best-so-far is aggressive (roi_threshold 1.03, min_ships 3.24,
  reinforce_beta 1.70) yet still loses. Two takeaways: (1) it's still in the random-startup phase, so don't over-read it, but (2) the early signal confirms the config is a
  tight optimum and, crucially, naive aggression overextends and loses. This is the most important nuance: the answer isn't "more aggression," it's calibrated aggression
  — which is exactly what search buys you (lookahead tells you which aggressive moves don't blow up). It matches your cloud-Claude's ladder: 1793 = deeper search +
  calibrated aggression.</important>

  Your min_ships_to_launch hunch — backwards (gently)

  min_ships_to_launch is the minimum garrison a planet needs before it's allowed to launch. Turning it up makes planets hoard more before acting → fewer, more conservative
  launches. To increase aggression you turn it down (and lower roi_threshold, lower reinforce_size_beta). The Optuna search agrees — its best-so-far has min_ships=3.24
  (down from 4.0). So your instinct toward aggression is right; the specific knob direction is inverted.

  Your human strategy (the static-planet land-grab) — genuinely good, partly already in there

  Your "dispatch ~half each turn, send ~1.5× for guaranteed close captures, reinforce frontier from home, cascade outward" — comet_reaper already does versions of this:
  safe_drain sends the safe surplus; capture_floor sizes the wave to guarantee capture (+ a reinforcement margin); and the pressure-gradient regroup marshals ships from
  safe rear planets toward stressed frontier planets. The novel, untested piece is "prioritize the closest static (non-rotating) planets first" — the engine ranks targets
  by proximity + competitive value, not by static-vs-rotating. Static planets stay in safe space and are the reliable production base, so weighting them could be a real
  edge. That's a clean, testable hypothesis (a target-scoring feature + knob) — exactly the kind of thing the autoresearch loop should sweep.

  Potential fields + CFR (you asked me to ultrathink)

  - Potential field w/ future planet positions: mid-EV and a natural fit. comet_reaper already lead-aims (accounts for where a planet will be at arrival), but it doesn't
  prioritize targets by future geometry. A potential-field overlay — value a planet higher if it's rotating toward your territory (cheap to defend/exploit) and lower if
  drifting into a rival's zone — is a concrete scoring feature to test on the gauntlet. Pairs with your static-planet idea (static = a "fixed well" in the field).
  - CFR — honest take: theoretically elegant, wrong-fit here, low ROI. CFR solves imperfect-information games (poker — hidden cards) by minimizing regret toward an
  unexploitable mixed equilibrium. Orbit Wars is perfect-information (you see the whole board), simultaneous-move, and 4-player. CFR's unexploitability guarantee is strong
  only in 2-player zero-sum; in 4-player general-sum, "Nash equilibrium" isn't unique and equilibrium play isn't even the best response to the actual opponents you face.
  So full CFR is a big research project that buys little here. The one useful nugget: if we discover specific opponents are exploiting us, a touch of mixed-strategy
  randomization helps — but best-responding via search (predict the opponent, counter it) is far higher-EV for this game than equilibrium-solving. I'd shelve CFR.

